  wolverhampton: {
    localMovingInfo: `Wolverhampton is the largest city in the Black Country and it feels it — a proper city centre with a university, a train station, and a ring road that's just as confusing as Coventry's if you don't know it. The WV1 and WV2 postcodes cover the centre: flats above shops, Victorian terraces, and the area around the station and the Grand Theatre. The one-way system around the ring road is the main challenge for central moves. WV3 and WV4 take in Penn and Compton — the leafy western suburbs where larger properties often have driveways and gardens. Tettenhall, one of Wolverhampton's most sought-after areas, sits on a ridge overlooking the city and has a village high street with Georgian and Victorian properties. WV5-WV6 extend into the semi-rural areas towards Bridgnorth. WV7-WV11 cover the northern and eastern suburbs — Wednesfield, Ashmore Park, Fallings Park — mostly post-war estates with reasonable access. The A41 Birmingham New Road is the main route south to Birmingham and it's one of the busiest roads in the Black Country. The M54 starts at Wolverhampton and heads west towards Telford and Shrewsbury. Wolverhampton has no Clean Air Zone. A verified mover reviewing a Wolverhampton request checks ring-road access, whether the property is in the city centre or suburbs, and A41/M54 timing.`,
  },

